about 14,000 times!&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.bdlive.co.za/business/financial/2016/05/23/standard-bank-confirms-it-has-been-target-of-fraud-in-japan&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Standard Bank has confirmed the robbery&lt;/a&gt; to South African media that the event occurred, and has estimated the damage to the bank at around R200m (200 million South African Rand, or about $12.7M USD or about 1.4 billion Japanese Yen).&amp;nbsp; But is it truly an &quot;Unlimited&quot; attack?&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The story was first reported in the 22MAY2016 Mainichi Daily News as &quot;&lt;a href=&quot;http://mainichi.jp/english/articles/20160522/p2g/00m/0dm/044000c&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;1.4 billion yen stolen from 1,400 convenience store ATMs across Japan&lt;/a&gt;&quot;.&amp;nbsp; The ATM machines are located in 7-Eleven convenience stores throughout Tokyo and 16 prefectures around the country.&amp;nbsp; The ATM machines in 7-Eleven stores in Japan are part of the bank network associated with Seven Bank.&amp;nbsp; Seven Bank&#39;s website invites international visitors to Japan to use their ATMs at 7-Eleven stores &quot;Day or Night&quot; which may be part of the appeal to these criminals.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;table align=&quot;center&quot; cellpadding=&quot;0&quot; cellspacing=&quot;0&quot; class=&quot;tr-caption-container&quot; style=&quot;margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;tbody&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://2.bp.blogspot.com/-n4uCTJ-N-qg/V0R6NqP4bwI/AAAAAAAABFA/vxcqm9hb6bAIFSCWuOIWo2J81TRWHcDEgCLcB/s1600/SevenBankATMs.jpg&quot; imageanchor=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;&quot;&gt;&lt;img border=&quot;0&quot; height=&quot;141&quot; src=&quot;https://2.bp.blogspot.com/-n4uCTJ-N-qg/V0R6NqP4bwI/AAAAAAAABFA/vxcqm9hb6bAIFSCWuOIWo2J81TRWHcDEgCLcB/s400/SevenBankATMs.jpg&quot; width=&quot;400&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class=&quot;tr-caption&quot; style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;&gt;www.sevenbank.co.jp/intlcard/index2.html &lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/tbody&gt;&lt;/table&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Several unique things happened in this account.&amp;nbsp; In previous &quot;Unlimited&quot; attacks, a very small  number of accounts have had a related debit card &quot;cloned&quot; by making an  exact copy of the magnetic stripe of the card.&amp;nbsp; In the past, an intruder  onto the bank&#39;s network has been able to adjust the daily withdrawal  limits of the cards, and reverse transactions, so that the same account  could be used to perform hundreds or thousands of withdrawals.&amp;nbsp; The attacks are referred to as &quot;Unlimited&quot; attacks because a single account with a very small balance could be used to front millions of dollars worth of transactions, because each transaction is immediately reversed by the intruders who monitor the carefully orchestrated attack.&amp;nbsp; In the case of the most famous Unlimited attack, &quot;&lt;a href=&quot;http://garwarner.blogspot.com/2009/11/9-million-world-wide-bank-robbery.html&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;The $9 Million World-Wide Bank Robbery&lt;/a&gt;&quot;, forty-four accounts were used to withdraw funds from 2,100 ATM machines in at least 280 cities around the world in a single evening.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;In this case, it is not clear if this is what happened, primarily because the published reports say that at least 1,600 Standard Bank customers&#39; accounts were used to perform the transactions. If this is true, with an estimate of 100 criminals involved in the &quot;cash-out&quot; portion of this robbery, that means on the average each criminal had access to 16 accounts that were unique to that criminal.&amp;nbsp; Also, with 1600 accounts in play, that means the average account holder&#39;s account would only have faced $7900 USD in charges.&amp;nbsp; This, however, contradicts the description of events that the BBC quotes, when it says that Standard Bank reported that &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-36357182&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;&quot;a small number&quot; of fake cards&lt;/a&gt; were used in the event.&amp;nbsp; (The BBC article also places Standard Banks&#39; estimated lossed at $19.25m, which, if you do the math, shows they chose the higher of the two contradictory values being reported in South Africa of either R200m or R300m.&amp;nbsp; R200m matches all of other figures being thrown about, while R300m is 50% higher.)&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;In my humble opinion, I believe that a journalist not versed in this type of cybercrime heard that 1600 counterfeit cards were used and assumed that they must belong to 1600 customers.&amp;nbsp; The key difference, and the most important with regards to Standard Bank, is that in a true &quot;Unlimited&quot; attack, the criminals would need to be controlling ATM accounts and logs INSIDE the Standard Bank network with administrator-level privileges.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The Japan Times say &quot;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.japantimes.co.jp/news/2016/05/22/national/crime-legal/convenience-store-atm-heist-sees-%C2%A51-4-billion-stolen-two-hours-across-japan/#.V0R3oeTMkd0&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Japanese police have put suspects belonging to a Malaysian group&lt;/a&gt; on an international wanted list&quot; relating to this event.&amp;nbsp; In reports from 2014, Japanese officials say that &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2014-12-17/chinese-criminals-blamed-for-record-japan-bank-cybertheft&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Chinese students are often used as money mules &lt;/a&gt;in Japan for withdrawing cash on behalf of organized cyber criminals, in much the same way that &lt;a href=&quot;http://garwarner.blogspot.com/2010/10/fbis-operation-aching-mule.html&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Russian money mules&lt;/a&gt; are used to withdraw cash from American banks.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;</content><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://garwarner.blogspot.com/feeds/4395639552681012185/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://garwarner.blogspot.com/2016/05/unlimited-atm-attack-in-japan-against.html#comment-form' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/35783026/posts/default/4395639552681012185'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/35783026/posts/default/4395639552681012185'/><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://garwarner.blogspot.com/2016/05/unlimited-atm-attack-in-japan-against.html' title='&quot;Unlimited&quot; ATM attack in Japan against South Africa&#39;s Standard Bank'/><author><name>Gary Warner, UAB / PhishMe</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/10822366940133384061</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email><gd:image rel='http://schemas.google.com/g/2005#thumbnail' width='32' height='32' src='//3.bp.blogspot.com/-css1_Txun8Q/VyeaNCPlI_I/AAAAAAAABEY/suKqHx3YvqAccGORXzJeg6Ie7zJ_LcjTgCK4B/s220/20792047913_7f098b2b60_o%2B%2528638x640%2529.jpg'/></author><media:thumbnail xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" url="https://2.bp.blogspot.com/-n4uCTJ-N-qg/V0R6NqP4bwI/AAAAAAAABFA/vxcqm9hb6bAIFSCWuOIWo2J81TRWHcDEgCLcB/s72-c/SevenBankATMs.jpg" height="72" width="72"/><thr:total>0</thr:total></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-35783026.post-1170884062912972204</id><published>2016-05-02T08:53:00.001-07:00</published><updated>2016-05-02T12:54:08.182-07:00</updated><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="ACLU"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="botnets"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="Congress"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="EFF"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="Federal Rules of Practice and Procedure"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="Rule 41"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="Search warrants"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="Supreme Court"/><title type='text'>Rule 41 Changes: Search and Seizure when you don&#39;t know the Computer&#39;s location</title><content type='html'>This one is for the legal geeks ...&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;This weekend, the EFF published an article &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.eff.org/deeplinks/2016/04/rule-41-little-known-committee-proposes-grant-new-hacking-powers-government&quot;&gt;With Rule 41, Little-Known Committee Proposed to Grant New Hacking Powers to the Government&lt;/a&gt;.  This discussion pits the privacy advocates such as EFF against the Department of Justice folks who want more powers to gather data.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; The EFF is&amp;nbsp; crying foul and making it seem that these changes are being sneaked through in the dead of night, while the DOJ is pointing out how reasonable the changes are. Multiple public hearings were held and written testimony received and used (including theirs) to amend the rule change.&amp;nbsp; This conversation has been going on since early 2014.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;That said, it is entirely possible that the Technology Folks who probably have the best insights into how these rules would intersect with the Modern Internet probably have the least understanding of how these rules work.&amp;nbsp; I&#39;ve tried to put together a brief backgrounder, followed by links to some of the key Comments and Testimony received thus far.&amp;nbsp; IF YOU DON&#39;T WANT THIS TO BE LAW, YOUR CONGRESSMAN NEEDS TO STOP IT.&amp;nbsp; (conversely, if you are technical and see no problem with it, you might share those thoughts with your Congressman as well.)&amp;nbsp; Here&#39;s House.gov&#39;s &quot;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.house.gov/representatives/find/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Find Your Representative&lt;/a&gt;&quot; page in case this whole concept of representative government is new to you.&amp;nbsp; They can&#39;t REPRESENT you if you don&#39;t TALK TO THEM!&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;h3&gt;What are the Federal Rules of Practice and Procedure?&lt;/h3&gt;The Federal Rules of Practice and Procedure were created in 1934 under the &quot;&lt;a href=&quot;http://federalevidence.com/rules-enabling-act&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Rules Enabling Act (&lt;/a&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.blogger.com/null&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;28 U.S.C. Â§ 2071-2077&lt;/a&gt;).&amp;nbsp; The key pieces of the act are in 2071 and 2072 -- (2071) &quot;The Supreme Court and all courts established by Act of Congress may from    time to time prescribe rules for the conduct of their business. Such rules shall    be consistent with Acts of Congress and rules of practice and procedure prescribed    under section 2072 of this title.&quot; and (2072) &quot;The Supreme Court shall have the power to prescribe general rules of practice and procedure and rules of evidence for cases in the United States district courts (including proceedings before magistrate judges thereof) and courts of appeals.&quot;&amp;nbsp; The rest of the act lays out how the &quot;Judicial Conference&quot; plays a role in this work.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;h3&gt;Who is the Judicial Conference?&lt;/h3&gt;Back on October 1, 2015, U.S. Supreme Court Justice John Roberts named the chairs for his six Advisory Committees.  One of the powers of being the Chief Justice is that you get to appoint who the chairs of the Committees of the Judicial Conference, who are the leaders who decide what the Federal Rules are going to be, pending approval first by the Supreme Court, and then by Congress. There are actually eleven Judicial Conference committee chairs. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;Judge Richard R. Clifton (Ninth Circuit) --  Committee on Federal-State Jurisdiction&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Judge Allyson K. Duncan (Fourth Circuit) -- Committee on International Judicial Relations&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Judge Lawrence F. Stengen (Eastern District of Pennsylvania) -- Committe on Judicial Resources&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Judge David R. Herndon (Soutern District of Illinois) -- Committee on Judicial Security&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Judge John D. Bates (District of DC) -- Advisory Committee on Civil Rules&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Judge Donald W. Molloy (Montana District) -- Advisory Committee on Criminal Rules&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Previously named chairs: &lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;Judge Lawrence L. Piersol (South Dakota) -- Committee on Audits and Administrative Office Accountability&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Chief Judge Catherine C. Blake (Maryland) -- Committee on Defender Services&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Judge Anthony J. Scirica (Third Circuit) -- Committee on Judicial Conduct and Disability&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Judge Jeffrey S. Sutton (Sixth Circuit) -- Committee on Rules of Practice and Procedure&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;Judge Steven M. Colloton (Eighth Circuit) -- Advisory Committee on Appellate Rules &lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;On October 9, 2015, Jeffrey Sutton, the chair of the Committe on Rules of Practice and Procedure, sent their &quot;Summary of Proposed Amendements to the Federal Rules&quot; to the Supreme Court.  The document is co-signed by the Chairs of the Advisory Committees (Appellate Rules, Bankruptcy Rules, Civil Rules, Criminal Rules, and Evidence Rules).&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&amp;nbsp;The full package contained several rules, and per the normal process, the Supreme Court had until May 1, 2016 to forward them to Congress if they agreed with them (This is the action that just happened, triggering the current media round) who then has until December 1, 2016 to take &quot;contrary action&quot; if they don&#39;t want them to become the law of the land.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;h3&gt;What did the Judicial Conference ask for this year?&lt;/h3&gt;The items in the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.uscourts.gov/file/18641/download&quot;&gt;2015-2016 Supreme Court Package of Proposed Rule Changes&lt;/a&gt; package consisted of 244 pages of committee notes, Comments from the open comment period, and responses to them.  Here is an outline of the Changes proposed, with our focus being on V. B. - Venue to Obtain Warrants for Remote Electronic Search:  &lt;br /&gt;&lt;dl&gt;&lt;dt&gt;&lt;u&gt;I.Elimination of the Three-Day Rule for Items Served Electronically.&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dd&gt;basically the &quot;three-day rule&quot; had been set up to allow for the time it takes to mail a package through the U.S. Postal Service.  The point of this rule change is that if things are being delivered electronically, whey do we need this three day delay?&lt;/dd&gt;&lt;dt&gt;&lt;u&gt;II. Federal Rules of Appellate Procured&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dt&gt;A.Inmate-Filing Rules&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dt&gt;B.Late Post-Judgment Motions and Appeals Time&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dt&gt;C.Length Limits for Briefs and Other Documents&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dt&gt;D.Amicus Filings in Connection with Rehearing&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dt&gt;E.Technical Amendment&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dt&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dt&gt;&lt;u&gt;III. Federal Rules of Bankruptcy Procedure&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dt&gt;A. Procedures for International Bankruptcy Cases&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dt&gt;B. Chapter 13 Notices&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dt&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dt&gt;&lt;u&gt;IV. Federal Rules of Civil Procedure&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dt&gt;A. Service on a Foreign Corporation&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dt&gt;B. Service&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dt&gt;C. Venue Technical Amendment&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dt&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dt&gt;&lt;u&gt;V. Federal Rules of Criminal Procedure&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dt&gt;A. Service on Foreign Corporate Defendants&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dd&gt;&quot;The proposed amendment to Criminal Rule 4 addresses service of a summons on organizational defendants that have no agent or principal place of business within the United States. (...) Given the increasing number of criminal prosecutions involving foreign entities, the Advisory Committee agreed that the Criminal Rules should provide a mechanism for foreign service on an organization.&quot;&lt;/dd&gt;&lt;dt&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;u&gt;B. Venue to Obtain Warrants for Remote Electronic Searches&lt;/u&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/dt&gt;&lt;dd&gt;More below ... &lt;/dd&gt;&lt;/dl&gt;&lt;h2&gt;Rule 41 Amendment: Venue to Obtain Warrants for Remote Electronic Searches &lt;/h2&gt;The text below comes from the aforementioned &quot;Supreme Court Package&quot; ... specifically from pp.198-200, for the text of the rule change itself, and from pp.200-202, for the Subcommittee comments.&amp;nbsp; Further explanation is from pp.225- labeled &quot;Excerpt from the September 2015 Report of the Judicial Conference&quot; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;h2&gt;&amp;nbsp;Rule 41. Search and Seizure&lt;/h2&gt;(b) &lt;b&gt;Venue for a warrant Application.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/b&gt;At the request of a federal law enforcement officer or an attorney for the government:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;(6) a magistrate judge with authority in any district where activities related to a crime may have occurred has authority to issue a warrant to use remote access to search electronic storage media and to seize or copy electronically stored information located within or outside that district if:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;(A) the district where the media or information is located has been concealed through technological means; or&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;(B) in an investigation of a violation of 18 U.S.C. Â§ 1030(a)(5), the media are protected computers that have been damaged without authorization and are located in five or more districts.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;(f) Executing and Returning the Warrant.&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;(1) &lt;i&gt;Warrant to Search for and Seize a Person or Property.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;i&gt;(C) Reciept.&amp;nbsp; &lt;/i&gt;The officer executing the warrant must give a copy of the warrant and a receipt for the property taken to the person from whom, or from whose premises, the property was taken or leave a copy of the warrant and receipt at the place where the officer took the property.&amp;nbsp; For a warrant to&amp;nbsp;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt; &lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;use remote access to search electronic storage media and seize or copy electronically stored information, the officer must make reasonable efforts to serve a copy of the warrant and receipt on the person whose property was searched or who possessed the information that was seized or copied.&amp;nbsp; Service may be accomplished by any means, including electronic means, reasonably calculated to reach that person.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;h2&gt;Subcommittee notes on (b)(6)&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;Subcommittee notes on (b)(6):&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;i&gt;Subdivision (b)(6).&lt;/i&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt; &lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;i&gt;The amendment provides that in two specific circumstances a magistrate judge in a district where activities related to a crime may have occurred has authority to issue a warrant to use remote access to search electronic storage media and seize or copy electronically stored information even when that media or information is or may be located outside of the district.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;i&gt;First, subparagraph (b)(6)(A)&lt;/i&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt; &lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;i&gt;provides authority to issue a warrant to use remote access within or outside that district when the district&lt;b&gt; in which the media or information is located is not known because of the use of technology such as anonymizing software&lt;/b&gt;.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;i&gt;Second, (b)(6)(B) allows a warrant to use remote access within or outside the district in an investigation of a violation of 18 U.S.C. Â§ 1030(a)(5) &lt;/i&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;if the media to be searched are protected computers that have been damaged without authorization, and they are located in many&lt;br /&gt;districts. Criminal activity under 18 U.S.C. Â§ 1030(a)(5) (such as the creation and control of âbotnetsâ) may target multiple computers in several districts.&amp;nbsp;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;In investigations of this nature, the amendment would eliminate the burden of attempting to secure multiple warrants in numerous districts, and allow a single judge to oversee the investigation.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;i&gt;As used in this rule, the terms âprotected computerâ&amp;nbsp; and âdamageâ have the meaning provided in 18 U.S.C. Â§ 1030(e)(2) &amp;amp; (8).&lt;/i&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;i&gt;The amendment does not address constitutional questions, such as the specificity of description that the Fourth Amendment may require in a warrant for remotely searching electronic storage media or seizing or copying electronically stored information, leaving the application of this and other constitutional standards to ongoing case law development.&lt;/i&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;/b&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;b&gt;&lt;i&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;/b&gt; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;h2&gt;Excerpt from the September 2015 Report of the Judicial Conference re:Rule 41&lt;/h2&gt;I&#39;ll place the footnote first ... &quot;At present, Rule 41(b) authorizes search warrants for property located outside the judge&#39;s district in only four situations: (1) for property in the district that might be removed before execution of the warrant; (2) for tracking devices installed in the district, which may be monitored outside the district; (3) for investigations of domestic or international terrorism; and (4) for property located in a U.S. territory or a U.S. diplomatic or consular mission.&quot;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Now from the memo:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The proposed amendment to Rule 41 addresses venue for obtaining warrants for certain remote electronic searches. At present, the rule generally limits searches to locations within a district, with a few specified exceptions. The proposal to amend Rule 41 is narrowly tailored to address two increasingly common situations in which the existing territorial or venue requirements may hamper the investigation of serious federal crimes:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;(1) where the warrant sufficiently describes the computer to be searched but the district within which that computer is located is unknown, and&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;(2) where the investigation requires law enforcement to coordinate searches of numerous computers in numerous districts.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The proposal would address this issue by amending Rule 41(b) to include two additional exceptions to the list of out-of-district searches permitted under that subsection.(see footnote above) Language in anew subsection 41(b)(6) would authorize a court to issue a warrant to use remote access to search&lt;br /&gt;electronic storage media and seize electronically stored information inside or outside of the&lt;br /&gt;district:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;(1) when a suspect has used technology to conceal the location of the media to be&lt;br /&gt;searched; or&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;(2) in an investigation into a violation of the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act, 18&lt;br /&gt;U.S.C. Â§ 1030(a)(5), when the media to be searched include damaged computers located in five&lt;br /&gt;or more districts.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The proposal also amends Rule 41(f)(1)(C) to specify the process for providing notice of a remote access search.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;As expected, the proposed amendment generated significant response; the Advisory&lt;br /&gt;Committee received 44 written comments, and 8 witnesses testified at a public hearing in&lt;br /&gt;Washington, D.C. In addition, the Department of Justice submitted written responses to the&lt;br /&gt;issues raised by the comments and testimony. Many commentators raised concerns regarding the&lt;br /&gt;substantive limits on government searches, which are not affected by the proposal. In fact, much&lt;br /&gt;of the opposition reflected a misunderstanding of the scope of the proposal. The proposal&lt;br /&gt;addresses venue; it does not itself create authority for electronic searches or alter applicable&lt;br /&gt;constitutional requirements.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The Advisory Committee approved revisions to the published proposal aimed at&lt;br /&gt;clarifying the procedural nature of the proposed amendment. It changed the published caption&lt;br /&gt;from âAuthority to Issue a Warrantâ to âVenue for a Warrant Applicationâ and revised the&lt;br /&gt;Committee Note to state that the constitutional requirements for the issuance of a warrant are not&lt;br /&gt;altered by the amendment. The Advisory Committee also approved revisions to the notice&lt;br /&gt;provision and accompanying Committee Note that directly respond to points raised by&lt;br /&gt;commentators. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;h3&gt;Some of the Comments and Witnesses&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://cdt.org/files/2014/10/CDT-Rule41-Written-Statement-final-20141024.pdf&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;The Center for Democracy &amp;amp; Technology&lt;/a&gt; submitted an 11-page PDF prior to testifying before the Judicial Conference on this matter Friday, October 24, 2014.&amp;nbsp; Their big &quot;Legal Implication&quot; was &quot;The proposed modification to FRCrmP Rule 41 would make policy decisions about important questions of law that are not currently settled and would best be resolved through legislation.&quot;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The ACLU submitted a 21-page PDF comment April 4, 2014 -- &quot;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.aclu.org/sites/default/files/assets/aclu_comments_on_rule_41.pdf&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;ACLU Comment on the Proposed Amendment to Rule 41 Concerning Remote Searches of Electronic Storage Media&lt;/a&gt;&quot;-- prior to the Advisory Committee&#39;s public hearing on the subject, April 7-8, 2014.&amp;nbsp; Great reading!&amp;nbsp; I especially appreciated this being cast into the area of Cloud Data challenges -- see the section &quot;Remote Searches of Cloud Data Pose Fourth Amendment, Statutory, and Policy Problems.&quot;&amp;nbsp; This report also addresses one of my chief concerns, which I call &quot;Venue Shopping.&quot;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; In a large botnet, victims exist in every single Federal District.&amp;nbsp; This means that if I found a &quot;friendly judge&quot; in any district, I could just flood all my requests through that jurisdiction.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Many of these same concerns were re-addressed to the committee by the ACLU who also presented testimony for the October 24, 2014 meeting.&amp;nbsp; (See &quot;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.aclu.org/files/assets/aclu_comment_on_remote_access_proposal.pdf&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Second ACLU Comment on Rule 41&lt;/a&gt;&quot;)&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Richard Salgado also shared &lt;a href=&quot;http://googlepublicpolicy.blogspot.com/2015/02/a-small-rule-change-that-could-give-us.html&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Google&#39;s Comments on the Proposed Amendment to Rule 41&lt;/a&gt; (13FEB2015) raising these and many similar concerns, and specifically pointing out that the Mutual Legal Assistance Treaties exist for exactly the purpose of international cooperation on searches.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Should we really be conducting extra-territorial searches without even knowing what territory the seized material is located in?&amp;nbsp; Google also mentions the concern that many VPNs may find themselves subject to this search because of the anonymizing function that a VPN can perform, even if the VPN is a legitimate bank, retailer, or other business merely seeking to better secure their users.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.regulations.gov/#!documentDetail;D=USC-RULES-CR-2014-0004-0008&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;EFF was represented in testimony (November 5, 2014) by Amie Stepanovich&lt;/a&gt;, the Senior Policy Counsel at Access, &quot;an international digital rights non-governmental organization founded in the wake of the 2009 Iranian post-election crackdown.&quot;&amp;nbsp; She points out in her testimony that this is a broad expansion of the powers defined in the Computer Fraud and Abuse Act (CFAA) which may, due to the nature of botnets that use distributed Command and Control, result in searching and seizing evidence from various protected classes of computer users, all of which have been victims of botnets, including journalists, dissidents, whistleblowers, members of the military, lawmakers and world leaders! &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The list of all 55 received comments can be accessed at&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.regulations.gov/#!docketBrowser;rpp=25;po=0;dct=PS;D=USC-RULES-CR-2014-0004&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt; Regulations.gov&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Other significant commentors included:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.regulations.gov/#!documentDetail;D=USC-RULES-CR-2014-0004-0011&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Kevin Bankston, for New America&#39;s Open Technology Institute&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.regulations.gov/#!documentDetail;D=USC-RULES-CR-2014-0004-0027&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Bruce Moyer, for the National Association of Assistant United States Attorneys&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.regulations.gov/#!documentDetail;D=USC-RULES-CR-2014-0004-0040&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;David Bitkower, for the U.S. Department of Justice&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&amp;nbsp;This memo presents three &quot;warrant scenarios&quot; and attempts to show how they would not be violations of Fourth Amendment rights of protection from unreasonable search.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.regulations.gov/#!documentDetail;D=USC-RULES-CR-2014-0004-0012&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Comments on Proposed Remote Search Rules by professors Steven Bellovin of Columbia, Matt Blaze of University of Pennsylvania, and Susan Landau of Worcester Polytechnic Institute&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;This memo points out concerns about trying to address very specific botnet features in the face of the unknown - how botnets will change in the future,&amp;nbsp; as well as raising some very key questions about Chain of Custody and Authenticity of Evidence when we have no idea where the computer is providing the evidence in question.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;</content><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="Bank of Bangladesh"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="Casinos"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="Maia Santos-Deguito"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="malware"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="RCBC"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="SWIFT"/><title type='text'>Is the Bank of Bangladesh ready for the Global Economy? </title><content type='html'>On February 4, 2016, more than $100 Million USD were stolen from the Bank of Bangladesh&#39;s foreign exchange reserves &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/12/opinion/bangladeshs-other-banking-scam.html&quot;&gt;housed at the Federal Reserve Bank&lt;/a&gt; in New York.   The hackers had actually attempted to steal US$951 Million, in a series of three dozen SWIFT wire transfers, but were thwarted when an alert staff member found some suspicious misspellings in the name of the organization used for the fifth transfer.  Five transfers were completed totaling US$101 Million, although a $20M transfer to a non-profit organization in Sri Lanka was reversed due to the spelling error, which called them &quot;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.theguardian.com/business/2016/mar/10/spelling-mistake-prevented-bank-heist&quot;&gt;Shalika Fandation&lt;/a&gt;&quot; instead of &quot;Foundation,&quot; causing a deeper look at the transfer, and stopping an additional US$850 Million of queued transfers to other organizations.  Stealing $1 Billion is huge, but especially for Bangladesh, whose total foreign currency holdings are $27 Billion.&lt;P&gt; &lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://3.bp.blogspot.com/-ga-eTBJr8WQ/VxuCxGB3BbI/AAAAAAAABDg/qYfbHm7BObYbtPtkGJgRomaqkczTENGBQCLcB/s1600/bank.of.bangladesh.jpg&quot; imageanchor=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;&quot;&gt;&lt;img border=&quot;0&quot; src=&quot;https://3.bp.blogspot.com/-ga-eTBJr8WQ/VxuCxGB3BbI/AAAAAAAABDg/qYfbHm7BObYbtPtkGJgRomaqkczTENGBQCLcB/s320/bank.of.bangladesh.jpg&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt; The four successful transfers, totaling US$81 Million were sent to an account in the Philippines at Rizal Commercial Banking Corporation.  Hearings held by the Philippines Senate revealed that these accounts had been opened nine months earlier by two Chinese residents. Kim Wong (AKA Kam Sin Wong) claims that he only acted as an interpreter to assist two other Chinese nationals, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.theepochtimes.com/n3/2019885-two-chinese-people-suspected-in-bangladesh-bank-theft/&quot;&gt;Gao Shu Hua and Ding Zhi Ze&lt;/a&gt;, from Beijing and Macau.&lt;P&gt;  Gao and Wong are &quot;junket operators&quot; who are among the many small boat captains who are thought to ferry gamblers between the casinos in Macau and the Philippines.&lt;P&gt; In a series of quick financial operations, the funds were transferred from the Philippines to &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.rappler.com/business/features/125741-bangladesh-bank-philippine-banking-system&quot;&gt;three large local casinos&lt;/a&gt;: Midas Hotel and Casino, City of Dreams, and Solaire Resort and Casino, and then wired back to various international accounts, using the common trick of laundering the money by claiming it as gambling proceeds. Fortune magazine reported that in the case of &lt;a href=&quot;http://fortune.com/2016/03/29/81-million-stolen-from-bangladeshs-central-bank/&quot;&gt;Solaire, the $29 Million was credited to the account of a Macau-based high-rolling gambler&lt;/a&gt;. Somehow I don&#39;t think this is what Solaire was thinking of when they advertise &quot;The Great Exchange&quot;:  &lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://3.bp.blogspot.com/-908p2wNGF1Y/VxuDiX1dehI/AAAAAAAABDo/9EGtu6K0DuIMsKFBZfAKh-UffhAGJbeogCLcB/s1600/solaire.exchange.jpg&quot; imageanchor=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;&quot;&gt;&lt;img border=&quot;0&quot; src=&quot;https://3.bp.blogspot.com/-908p2wNGF1Y/VxuDiX1dehI/AAAAAAAABDo/9EGtu6K0DuIMsKFBZfAKh-UffhAGJbeogCLcB/s320/solaire.exchange.jpg&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt; At least one Philippine Senator, Sergio OsmeÃ±a III, claims that this is a planned loop hole in the Anti-Money Laundering Act.  Casinos lobbied the Senate heavily as the bill was being considered, and as a result, they are exempt from reporting suspicious financial transfers that most other commercial businesses are required to report.&lt;P&gt; &lt;h2&gt;RCBC &amp; Maia Santos-Deguito&lt;/H2&gt; &lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-gar-EIzvZRg/VxuGZuZq59I/AAAAAAAABD0/oRUWcVymdTgzTyAN58vEMy6I1Dgvd9NnACLcB/s1600/Deguito.jpg&quot; imageanchor=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;&quot;&gt;&lt;img border=&quot;0&quot; src=&quot;https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-gar-EIzvZRg/VxuGZuZq59I/AAAAAAAABD0/oRUWcVymdTgzTyAN58vEMy6I1Dgvd9NnACLcB/s320/Deguito.jpg&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;center&gt;(image from &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.philstar.com/headlines/2016/03/17/1563786/rcbc-branch-manager-tell-all-executive-session&quot;&gt;The Philippine Star&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;/CENTER&gt;&lt;P&gt; The Epoch Times reports that in at least one of these transfers, $22 Million was placed into the Jupiter Street branch of Philippines RCBC and $427,000 of those funds were withdrawn in cash and loaded into the car of Maia Santos Deguito, the brand manager.  The withdrawal was handled by Deguito&#39;s assistant, Angela Torres, who had the money delivered by armored car, took the money and placed it in a box, which was then transferred to a paper bag and placed in the branch manager&#39;s car. GMA News picks up the story of &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.gmanetwork.com/news/story/559507/money/companies/deguito-named-2-senior-rcbc-execs-who-could-be-part-of-bank-heist-guingona&quot;&gt;testimony from bank employees&lt;/a&gt; ... A bank employee said in testimony that Deguito told him, &quot;I would rather do this than me being killed or my family,&quot; claiming that her life had been threatened if she refused to participate in the illegal activity.  But when deposed herself, Deguito says her life was never threatened. The transfers from the Federal Reserve Bank of New York came to RCBC accounts under the names Michael F. Cruz, Jessie C. Lagrosas, Alfred S. Vergara, and Enrico T. Vasquez.  From there, $66M was withdrawn and consolidated into an account in the name of William So Go.  Deguito claims that Kim Wong, the front man for the Chinese pair, was a &quot;friend of bank President and CEO Lorenzo V. Tan.&quot;  Tan denies this, although he admits having seen Wong on a number of occasions.&lt;P&gt; The Treasurer of RCBC, Raul Victor Tan, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.rappler.com/business/industries/209-banking-and-financial-services/130289-rcbc-treasurer-raul-tan-quits&quot;&gt;has resigned&lt;/a&gt; &quot;out of decency and honor, and despite his lack of involvement.&quot;  Branch Manager Deguito reported to him and is largely believed to be the main point of contact between the bank and Gao Shu Hua.  RCBC&#39;s president was also placed on leave from March 23rd.  The Central Bank Governor in Bangladesh, Atiur Rahman, has been forced to resign as well. &lt;P&gt; &lt;H2&gt;My security is so bad that I&#39;m suing you!&lt;/H2&gt;According to The Epoch Times, the Bank of Bangladesh hired FireEye to investigate the situation.  The &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2016-03-18/hackers-stalked-bangladesh-bank-for-two-weeks-before-big-heist&quot;&gt;initial FireEye report&lt;/a&gt;, released March 16th, indicated that at least 32 compromised assets had been identified that were part of a complex malware scheme for harvesting credentials needed for the SWIFT transfers and erasing logs of the activity in question.&lt;P&gt; In much the same way that small businesses have attempted to file lawsuits against their banks when their lack of security has led to malware infections that drained their accounts, the Bank of Bangladesh announced through &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.aljazeera.com/news/2016/03/bangladesh-sue-bank-100m-lost-hackers-160309104435299.html&quot;&gt;Finance Minister AMA Muhith&lt;/a&gt; that they would sue the Federal Reserve Bank of New York.  In Al-Jazeera, Muhith is quoted as saying &quot;We&#39;ve heard that Federal Reserve Bank of New York has completely denied their responsibility.  They don&#39;t have any right.&quot;&lt;P&gt; But much like the small businesses who have lost those lawsuits once their ineptitude was put on display, Bank of Bangladesh may have trouble claiming the problem resided at the Fed.  On Friday, April 22nd, Reuters and BBC both released stories exposing the horrible security at Bank of Bangladesh.  The Reuters&#39; headline read &quot;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-fed-bangladesh-idUSKCN0XI1UO&quot;&gt;Bangladesh Bank exposed to hackers by cheap switches, no firewall: police&lt;/a&gt;&quot; while the BBC headline pronounced &quot;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-36110421&quot;&gt;$10 router blamed in Bangladesh bank hack&lt;/a&gt;&quot;.  A forensic investigator working on the Bangladesh team, Mohammad Shah Alam, says the investigation was complicated by the lack of log files available on these discount routers, but the larger problem is the illustrated lack of any care about security that choosing such a device indicates in the first place.  (It should be acknowledged that this contradicts the bank&#39;s statement that their firewall was penetrated by a sophisticated cyber attack:  &lt;P&gt; &lt;BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&quot;The central bank had put âzero tolerance securityâ and robust firewalls in place in the back office of its foreign currency division. But the cyber gang used a powerful malware to break the firewall and managed to send fake payment orders to the US bank, added the official.&quot; -- source: &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.asianews.network/content/bangladesh-bank-installing-monitoring-software-11440&quot;&gt;www.asianews.network/content/bangladesh-bank-installing-monitoring-software-11440&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/BLOCKQUOTE&gt;&lt;P&gt; &lt;H2&gt;Who can Join Our Network?&lt;/H2&gt;The bigger question raised in the Reuters story, though, is what responsibility should the western banking world hold in requesting to evaluate the security of those who would attach themselves to the trillions of dollars per day global financial markets?  In the United States our regulations require that a holder of Personally Identifiable Information should require proof of the security of those they interact with in a wide variety of settings.  HIPAA, the ruleset for protecting the privacy of your medical records, began requiring HIPAA-covered entities to take responsibility for the security of their vendors who may interact with sensitive records in 2013/2014. (See for example this story in IAPP -- &quot;&lt;a href=&quot;http://https://iapp.org/news/a/hipaa-changes-mean-tightening-up-vendor-relationships/&quot;&gt;HIPAA Changes Mean Tightening Up Vendor Relationships&lt;/a&gt;&quot;).  In the same way the Payment Card Industry standard, PCI, that protects the privacy of credit card information also requires any covered entity to perform Due Diligence of their third party vendors (See their 47 page guidance on the subject, &quot;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.pcisecuritystandards.org/documents/PCI_DSS_V3.0_Third_Party_Security_Assurance.pdf&quot;&gt;Information Supplement: Third-Party Security Assurance&lt;/a&gt;&quot;).&lt;P&gt; So if my Hospital is not allowed to exchange patient data with an insurance company before checking the security of their networks, systems, and applications, and my Grocery Store is not allowed to exchange credit card information with a financial services company before checking the security their networks, systems, and applications, why would SWIFT and the Federal Reserve Bank system be allowed to move billions of dollars on behalf of banks that don&#39;t have a firewall and have $10 routers bought second hand off the Internet?  SWIFT has announced they would be issuing &quot;written guidance&quot; to ensure their members are practicing &lt;a href=&quot;http://fortune.com/2016/03/20/swift-advisement-bangladesh-bank/&quot;&gt;proper security methods&lt;/a&gt;.  Hopefully these are more robust than those in their 2012 Whitepaper &quot;&lt;a href=&quot;https://www.swift.com/file/12866/download&quot;&gt;CPSS-IOSCO&#39;s Principles for Financial Market Infrastructures&lt;/a&gt;&quot;&gt;.  (To learn more see: &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.swift.com/about-us/discover-swift/information-security&quot;&gt;SWIFT: Information Security&lt;/a&gt;)&lt;P&gt; Probably because we are trying to lower the barriers of entry to banks from depressed economies.  &quot;Is it fair&quot; to require one of the poorest nations in the world to have to spend the same type of money that western nations spend on Internet security?  Perhaps not.  But until we do, these emerging economies are going to be a continual and growing target of the cyber criminals that are willing to invest &quot;western-style&quot; funds to accomplish heists that are truly worthy of a Hollywood movie.  &lt;h2&gt;Update 25APR2016 - BAE Analysis of SWIFT malware&lt;/h2&gt;Adrian Nish has published a blog post at BAE Systems Threat Research Blog &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.baesystemsai.blogspot.co.uk/2016/04/two-bytes-to-951m.html&quot;&gt;Two Bytes to $951M&lt;/A&gt; where he documents the behavior of the malware that was likely used in the Bank of Bangladesh unauthorized SWIFT transfers.  Malware that causes the SWIFT software running at the bank to bypass certain confirmations, and alter the print queue where messages are sent to hide the evidence of the transaction being performed.  Great analysis!  And making this attack far more advanced than the &quot;didn&#39;t have a firewall&quot; accusations being leveled.          </content><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://garwarner.blogspot.com/feeds/1210562631225186739/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://garwarner.blogspot.com/2016/04/is-bank-of-bangladesh-ready-for-global.html#comment-form' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/35783026/posts/default/1210562631225186739'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/35783026/posts/default/1210562631225186739'/><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://garwarner.blogspot.com/2016/04/is-bank-of-bangladesh-ready-for-global.html' title='Is the Bank of Bangladesh ready for the Global Economy? '/><author><name>Gary Warner, UAB / PhishMe</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/10822366940133384061</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email><gd:image rel='http://schemas.google.com/g/2005#thumbnail' width='32' height='32' src='//3.bp.blogspot.com/-css1_Txun8Q/VyeaNCPlI_I/AAAAAAAABEY/suKqHx3YvqAccGORXzJeg6Ie7zJ_LcjTgCK4B/s220/20792047913_7f098b2b60_o%2B%2528638x640%2529.jpg'/></author><media:thumbnail xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" url="https://3.bp.blogspot.com/-ga-eTBJr8WQ/VxuCxGB3BbI/AAAAAAAABDg/qYfbHm7BObYbtPtkGJgRomaqkczTENGBQCLcB/s72-c/bank.of.bangladesh.jpg" height="72" width="72"/><thr:total>0</thr:total></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-35783026.post-5477130074432883221</id><published>2016-04-14T09:02:00.001-07:00</published><updated>2016-04-14T09:03:27.864-07:00</updated><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="IRS"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="phishing"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="phishme"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="university phish"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="w2 phish"/><title type='text'>University &quot;Paperless W2&quot; Phish</title><content type='html'>Please visit my blog post at PhishMe to see information about a wide-spread campaign of &quot;Paperless W2&quot; phish that have been observed by at least twenty different universities.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://phishme.com/universities-face-w2-phish-president-impersonation/&quot;&gt;http://phishme.com/universities-face-w2-phish-president-impersonation/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt; Here&#39;s one example of the spam that University students, staff, and faculty have received, this one from Auburn University:&lt;P&gt; &lt;a href=&quot;http://phishme.com/universities-face-w2-phish-president-impersonation/&quot;&gt;&lt;IMG SRC=&quot;https://www.auburn.edu/images/oit/phishing/images/20160119-email.png&quot;&gt;&lt;/A&gt; (image source: www.auburn.edu/oit/news/article.php?id=422 ) </content><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://garwarner.blogspot.com/feeds/5477130074432883221/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://garwarner.blogspot.com/2016/04/university-paperless-w2-phish.html#comment-form' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/35783026/posts/default/5477130074432883221'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/35783026/posts/default/5477130074432883221'/><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://garwarner.blogspot.com/2016/04/university-paperless-w2-phish.html' title='University &quot;Paperless W2&quot; Apparently spammers are wise to this truth as well.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; When we saw spam messages this month imitating CNN talking about Donald Trump, our immediate thought was that this must be a malware campaign, such as the &lt;a href=&quot;http://garwarner.blogspot.com/2013/07/royal-baby-other-cnn-spam-leads-to.html&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;CNN &quot;Royal Baby&quot; spam&lt;/a&gt; we blogged about in 2013. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://2.bp.blogspot.com/-bo-Ic4FVZFg/VuaoO4iloKI/AAAAAAAABCA/PDTnJb0zKiA9b3upEEIrBBkjVGXqzlmBA/s1600/TrumpSpam1.jpg&quot; imageanchor=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;&quot;&gt;&lt;img border=&quot;0&quot; height=&quot;294&quot; src=&quot;https://2.bp.blogspot.com/-bo-Ic4FVZFg/VuaoO4iloKI/AAAAAAAABCA/PDTnJb0zKiA9b3upEEIrBBkjVGXqzlmBA/s320/TrumpSpam1.jpg&quot; width=&quot;320&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;PhishMe&#39;s malware analysts took a look and reported back that this was NOT a malware distribution campaign.&amp;nbsp; So what was it?&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;h3&gt;The Trump Spam&lt;/h3&gt;To start, we looked for spam during the month of March that had &quot;Trump&quot; in the subject line and &quot;CNN&quot; in the sender name, but did not actually get sent from CNN&#39;s IP addresses. There were many thousands to choose from, but only thirteen subject lines were used:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Subject: BREAKING:&amp;nbsp; Trump Explosion Shocks Audience&lt;br /&gt;Subject: BREAKING: Trump Scandal Could End it All...&lt;br /&gt;Subject: CNN: This Time Donald Trump Crossed the Line&lt;br /&gt;Subject: Donald Trump Explodes on Sunday Talk Show&lt;br /&gt;Subject: Donald Trump:&amp;nbsp; Here is my Secret Weapon&lt;br /&gt;Subject: Donald Trump:&amp;nbsp; I have a Secret Weapon&lt;br /&gt;Subject: Donald Trump: I&#39;M DONE&lt;br /&gt;Subject: Donald Trumps Reveals His Trump Card&lt;br /&gt;Subject: TRUMP ADMITS: Yes, It&#39;s Rigged&lt;br /&gt;Subject: Trump Debate Comment Stops the Show&lt;br /&gt;Subject: Trump Explodes at Debate, Stops the Show&lt;br /&gt;Subject: Trump Explodes on Sunday Talk Show&lt;br /&gt;Subject: Trump Reveals his Knockout Punch&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The &quot;sender name&quot; for these spam messages was selected from one of the following:&lt;br /&gt;CNN Breaking News&lt;br /&gt;CNN Breaking Now&lt;br /&gt;CNN Happening Now&lt;br /&gt;CNN News Now&lt;br /&gt;CNN Politics&lt;br /&gt;CNN Sunday&lt;br /&gt;CNN Updates&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;However, the email addresses had absolutely nothing to do with CNN or its domain name.&amp;nbsp; The userids were:&lt;br /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; info, news, notification, notify, or update&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;followed by many different domain names, including:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&amp;nbsp;allstayclear.com, bestbetterclass.com, childreneveryopen.com, eyealwaysher.com, &lt;br /&gt;followboatstreet.com, gavewantfar.com, heardwerethan.com, intuitivefinally.com, &lt;br /&gt;lessbooksure.com, offunitrain.com, pageobjectsystem.com, placewhenboy.com, &lt;br /&gt;pullamongmight.net, rainwhichcome.com, redanswercontain.com, restverysay.com, &lt;br /&gt;seemfarmlong.com, shegroundminute.com, sixletterwater.com, strongstoodstate.com, &lt;br /&gt;thingwoodscience.com, veryknewworld.com, warmfoundagain.com&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;These spam messages are from a group of spammers who specialize in using high interest headlines to do a many-level redirection that eventually lands the recipient of the email on a website promising some form of &quot;get rich quick&quot; scheme.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;h3&gt;Other Spam From Same IP Addresses (Walgreens, Google, Amazon)&lt;/h3&gt;By selecting the thirty most common spam-sending IP addresses for the CNN/Trump campaigns, we are able to learn about other favorite campaigns being run by the same group of spammers during the month of March 2016.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Subject:&amp;nbsp; (name), Your Walgreens Card is on Hold #(random number)&lt;br /&gt;Subject: Walgreens Pickup Notice (random number)&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;was popular at the beginning of the month, with&lt;br /&gt;March 1, 2016 From: info@bestbetterclass.com, info@followboatstreet.com,&lt;br /&gt;March 3, 2016 From: info@doneinchyes.com,&amp;nbsp; info@veryknewworld.com&lt;br /&gt;March 5, 2016 From: info@redanswercontain.com &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Beginning on March 8th, a popular &quot;Google is hiring&quot; scam began from the same spamming computers:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Subject: Google Inc. wants to work with you (89k working from home)&lt;br /&gt;Subject: Google Inc. has three positions available - $75.00 (hour)&lt;br /&gt;Subject: (3) New Positions Open With Google Inc. - Salary is 89K for 2016&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;From: home@heardwerethan.com, home@warmfoundagain.com, home@pullamongmight.net&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Then back to Walgreens, From: info@gavewantfar.com,&amp;nbsp; info@restverysay.com&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The Donald Trump / CNN spam was well mixed throughout on March 3, 4, 6, 7, 9, 11, 12&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;After a brief hard-core sex campaign on March 12th, on March 13, the spammers began an &quot;Amazon shopping voucher&quot; campaign:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Subject: (name) - Ready to use - your Amazon shopping voucher - active today&lt;br /&gt;Subject: (name) - Your Amazon Card&lt;br /&gt;Subject: (name) - So much at your fingertips - activate your Amazon cash voucher now&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;with sender names of &quot;Amazon.com.Credit, AmazonCard, ShopAmazon, and Amazon-Voucher and From: info@restverysay.com&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;h3&gt;The Redirection&lt;/h3&gt;In each of the spam campaigns, a single IP address was used as the source for each &quot;from domain&quot; and the destination URLs related to that email were all hosted on an oddly named host on the same domain.&amp;nbsp; Some examples include:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;table&gt;&lt;tbody&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;pageobjectsystem.com&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;89.46.63.82&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;mail.pageobjectsystem.com&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;intuitivefinally.com&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;94.176.163.119&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;b99.intuitivefinally.com&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;redanswercontain.com&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;72.1.242.156&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;97q.redanswercontain.com&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td&gt;sixletterwater.com&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;76.74.218.30&lt;/td&gt;&lt;td&gt;ffoz.sixletterwater.com&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/tbody&gt;&lt;/table&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Let&#39;s take a spam message that redirects us to &quot;smtp.friendroomdiffer.com&quot; as an example.&amp;nbsp; The URL that we are supposed to has a path that looks similar to this: (we&#39;ve replaced some characters to break the tracking)&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;ACRTl5OQU5IB/BIae1TW2BEpk3Z3SL/aLb6+cTbqj6whLaRcBYQTlIE8YcRUNvLS8xh5/zU31q3ruEfD3pXu64wV2NrIhYuwQKpcldGi/CRTw=&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;When we visit that URL, we are sent to &quot;7roitrack.com&quot; which then sends us to &quot;ih-trk.com&quot;&amp;nbsp; which then sends us to &quot;athome-profits.com&quot; which has a fake &quot;Breaking News&quot; page shown below:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; Spamming IPs? &lt;/h3&gt;For the spam-trackers who want to know . . .&amp;nbsp; those &quot;thirty most popular&quot; IP addresses on the Trump/CNN spam we saw are mostly in the US with a couple each from Canada and Romania, and one in Ireland.&amp;nbsp; In most cases, the criminal leases a box from a reseller who hosts services at one of these locations, and then spams as hard as possible until they get busted, then they rotate to a new IP and keep going.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Spamhaus has coined the term &quot;Snowshoe spammers&quot; for these people who often do single day, or even single scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="ATM"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="DOJ"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="Findikoglu"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="hacking"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="Matsumoto"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="Red Cross"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="Unlimited"/><title type='text'>&quot;Unlimited&quot; ATM Mastermind Ercan Findikoglu pleads guilty</title><content type='html'>One of the most fascinating types of cybercrime, in my opinion, is the Unlimited ATM attack.&amp;nbsp; There have been several such attacks over the years, as we&#39;ve written about in this blog previously, including:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;02JUL2008 - &lt;a href=&quot;http://garwarner.blogspot.com/2008/07/7-11-atm-hackers-more-details.html&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;7-11 ATM Hackers - More Details&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;07SEP2008 - &lt;a href=&quot;http://garwarner.blogspot.com/2008/09/is-analyzer-really-back-possible-return.html&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Is the Analyzer Really Back? (The return of Ehud Tenenbaum)&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;(Tenenbaum was transferred to the US, pled guilty to two other cases, sentenced in July 2012 to Time Served and ordered to pay $503,129 restitution)&amp;nbsp; &lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;li&gt;11NOV2009 - &lt;a href=&quot;http://garwarner.blogspot.com/2009/11/9-million-world-wide-bank-robbery.html&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;The $9 Million World-Wide Bank Robbery&lt;/a&gt; &lt;/li&gt;&lt;li&gt;09MAY2013 - &lt;a href=&quot;http://garwarner.blogspot.com/2013/05/atm-cashers-in-26-countries-steal-40m.html&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;ATM Cashers in 26 Countries Steal $40&lt;/a&gt;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/li&gt;&lt;/ul&gt;&lt;br /&gt;In an &quot;Unlimited&quot; attack, hackers gain access to the internal systems of a bank or banking network and are either able to &quot;reset&quot; ATM withdrawal limits or eliminate the limits altogether for a card or group of cards.&amp;nbsp; The magnetic stripe data from these cards are then widely distributed to &quot;cash-out crews&quot; who take responsibility for draining as many ATM cards as possible in their area, while each time a card is used, the hackers &quot;undo&quot; the transaction so that the card appears to have not been used.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-FhPBzIWVgKI/Vtykg8ZmhhI/AAAAAAAABBE/3AftWMCNCTI/s1600/Ercan-Findikoglu.jpg&quot; imageanchor=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;&quot;&gt;&lt;img border=&quot;0&quot; height=&quot;213&quot; src=&quot;https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-FhPBzIWVgKI/Vtykg8ZmhhI/AAAAAAAABBE/3AftWMCNCTI/s320/Ercan-Findikoglu.jpg&quot; width=&quot;320&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;33-year old Turkish citizen Ercan Findikoglu was charged with conducting three such Unlimited campaigns.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;In February 2011, $10M was withdrawn using the pre-paid debit cards distributed by the American Red Cross to disaster relief victims.&amp;nbsp; The cards were operated by JPMorgan Chase.&amp;nbsp; On February 27 and 28, 2011 a total of around 20 pre-paid debit cards were used in approximately 15,000 transactions to withdraw $10M from ATM machines in 18 countries, including ATMs in the Eastern District of New York.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;In Findikoglu&#39;s second Unlimited attack, pre-paid debit cards for the India-based company ECS, operated by National Bank of Ras Al-Khaimah PSC (RAKBANK) in the United Arab Emirates were used.&amp;nbsp; On December 21 and 22, 2012, approximately 5,000 transactions in at least 20 countries resulted in withdrawal of $5M.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;In the largest of his three documented Unlimited campaigns, enStage, a California-based payment processor, suffered an intrusion and had many cards stolen from its internal database.&amp;nbsp; A group of pre-paid debit cards for Bank Muscat in Oman were selected as the target, and on February 19 and 20, 2013, 36,000 transactions in 24 countries were used to steal $40M.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;ERCAN FINDIKOGLU, who called himself &quot;Segate&quot; or &quot;Predator&quot; online, was arrested in December of 2013 while visiting Germany.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://3.bp.blogspot.com/-XSZEApH4D_U/VtykjAipH0I/AAAAAAAABBI/gnRJXDKIIOA/s1600/findikoglu.indictment.jpg&quot; imageanchor=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;&quot;&gt;&lt;img border=&quot;0&quot; height=&quot;247&quot; src=&quot;https://3.bp.blogspot.com/-XSZEApH4D_U/VtykjAipH0I/AAAAAAAABBI/gnRJXDKIIOA/s320/findikoglu.indictment.jpg&quot; width=&quot;320&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;He was originally charged with 18 counts:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;(1)&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; CONSPIRACY TO DEFRAUD THE UNITED STATES&lt;br /&gt;(2-4) FRAUD ACTIVITY CONNECTED WITH COMPUTERS&lt;br /&gt;(5-6) ATTEMPT AND CONSPIRACY TO COMMIT MAIL FRAUD&lt;br /&gt;(7)&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; BANK FRAUD&lt;br /&gt;(8)&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; ATTEMPTS TO COMMIT AN OFFENSE&lt;br /&gt;(9-14) PRODUCES/TRAFFICS IN COUNTERFEIT DEVICE&lt;br /&gt;(15) MONEY LAUNDERING CONSPIRACY&lt;br /&gt;(16) MONEY LAUNDERING&lt;br /&gt;(17) TAMPERING WITH WITNESS, VICTIM, OR AN INFORMANT&lt;br /&gt;(18) INTIMIDATION OR FORCE AGAINST WITNESS&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;On June 24, 2015, Ercan was ordered into US detention, having been extradited from Germany.&amp;nbsp; The German courts in Frankfurt declared that Findikoglu was &quot;the  most-wanted computer hacker in the world and may face more than 247  years in prison if convicted of all U.S. charges&quot; (as quoted in  Bloomberg&#39;s story of 23JUN2015 - &quot;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.bloomberg.com/politics/articles/2015-06-23/turkish-man-accused-in-global-atm-heist-extradited-to-u-s-&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Most-wanted cybercriminal extradited to U.S. from Germany.&lt;/a&gt;&quot;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;As usual, the reality of sentencing varies dramatically from the overblown initial press release.&amp;nbsp; On March 1, 2016, All parties appeared before the honorable Judge Kiyo A. Matsumoto for a Change of Plea Hearing.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Sentencing is scheduled for July 12, 2016, but according to the BBC, prosecutors have agreed in a plea deal to limit his incarceration for &quot;between 11 and 15 years.&quot;&amp;nbsp; (See &quot;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-35716150&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;US bank hacker faces long jail time&lt;/a&gt;&quot;).&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Many of the &quot;Cash-out crews&quot; from these operations have been separately arrested and charged, while many others (the vast majority really) remain at large. &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;</content><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://garwarner.blogspot.com/feeds/5514286030905974249/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://garwarner.blogspot.com/2016/03/unlimited-atm-mastermind-ercan.html#comment-form' title='1 Comments'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/35783026/posts/default/5514286030905974249'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/35783026/posts/default/5514286030905974249'/><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://garwarner.blogspot.com/2016/03/unlimited-atm-mastermind-ercan.html' title='&quot;Unlimited&quot; ATM Mastermind Ercan Findikoglu pleads guilty'/><author><name>Gary Warner, UAB / PhishMe</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/10822366940133384061</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email><gd:image rel='http://schemas.google.com/g/2005#thumbnail' width='32' height='32' src='//3.bp.blogspot.com/-css1_Txun8Q/VyeaNCPlI_I/AAAAAAAABEY/suKqHx3YvqAccGORXzJeg6Ie7zJ_LcjTgCK4B/s220/20792047913_7f098b2b60_o%2B%2528638x640%2529.jpg'/></author><media:thumbnail xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" url="https://1.bp.blogspot.com/-FhPBzIWVgKI/Vtykg8ZmhhI/AAAAAAAABBE/3AftWMCNCTI/s72-c/Ercan-Findikoglu.jpg" height="72" width="72"/><thr:total>1</thr:total></entry><entry><id>tag:blogger.com,1999:blog-35783026.post-5619089591351316908</id><published>2016-01-24T14:06:00.001-08:00</published><updated>2016-01-24T14:07:47.765-08:00</updated><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="arrested"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="Botnet"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="DOJ"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="malware"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="USSS"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="Vovnenko"/><category scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="ZeuS"/><title type='text'>Vovnenko / Fly / MUXACC1 pleads guilty</title><content type='html'>Sergey Vovnenko pleads guilty&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;This week a Ukrainian hacker made famous for attempting to frame security journalist Brian Krebs by sending him heroin purchased on the Silk Road, had his day in court and chose to plead guilty.&amp;nbsp; Krebs blogged about his arrest in Italy in 2014 with the title &lt;a href=&quot;http://krebsonsecurity.com/2014/06/the-fly-has-been-swatted/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;The Fly Has Been Swatted&lt;/a&gt;, but now that a guilty plea has been entered, we can see the details of the case.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;In June 2013, a U.S. Secret Service agent swore out a criminal complaint against Vovnenko for crimes he committed against citizens in New Jersey.&amp;nbsp; Although we refer to &quot;Federal Crimes&quot; in most cyber crimes, charges can only be brought for damages local to the U.S. Attorney&#39;s office where the prosecution makes the charges.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;img border=&quot;0&quot; height=&quot;220&quot; src=&quot;http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-cq-15xi1cRY/VqU_caUGTMI/AAAAAAAAA_4/FztbKcLRtuc/s320/Vovnenko.Complaint.jpg&quot; width=&quot;320&quot; /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;From 2003 until 2013, the complaint states, SERGEY VOVNENKO, AKA Centurion, AKA Flycracker, AKA Flyck, AKA MUXACC1, AKA Stranier, ran various scams related to carding.&amp;nbsp; In a specific instance, cards were stolen &quot;on or about&quot; March 14, 2011 from a victim in Rutherford, NJ, violating Title 18 Section 371 of the Federal Code.&amp;nbsp; Many of the early attacks used SQL Injection to gain access to target computers that were accessible via the web and had access to databases of personally identifiable information and credit card data.&amp;nbsp; Vovnenko in particular advertised &quot;dumps&quot; services using both his Twitter account and an ICQ account.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Between 2009 and 2011, Vovnenko managed to plant malware on computers at &quot;Victim 1&quot; which is described as a &quot;global financial institution with millions of customer accounts&quot; that &quot;maintaned signficant infrastrucutre in New Jersey, including computer servers housing banking information located in New Jersey.&quot;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Vovnenko was an old-school carder.&amp;nbsp; He originally sold his dumps on the Shadowcrew website, which was shut down in 2004 by the U.S. Secret Service.&amp;nbsp; (This site is where Vovnenko began chatting with now infamous Data Breach king Albert Gonzalez.)&amp;nbsp; In 2008, Vovnenko used ICQ to chat with Vladislav Horohorin, the hacker known as &quot;BadB.&quot;&amp;nbsp; &lt;a href=&quot;https://www.fbi.gov/atlanta/press-releases/2013/international-credit-card-trafficker-sentenced-to-88-months-in-prison&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;BadB was sentenced to 88 months&lt;/a&gt; for trafficking in stolen cards and for his role in the $9M theft from Atlanta-based RBS WorldPay.&amp;nbsp; By 2010, Vovnenko was actively selling as &quot;Centurion&quot; on CardingWorld, Mazafaka, and Verified.ru.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Our complaintant testifies that on or about March 16, 201, Vovnenko chatted with another criminal who asked him to review his logs from his botnet to see whether he had IP addresses indicating that some of his bots were in the NJ-based Financial Institution known as &quot;Victim 1&quot; in the court documents.&amp;nbsp; He did, and was asked to plant an executable on that computer to give his co-conspirator remote control to the computer.&amp;nbsp; (We&#39;ve heard about this type of &quot;log selling&quot;, where a &quot;commodity botnet infection&quot; leads to targeted attacks at specific institutions before.&amp;nbsp; See my blog post about the Fox-IT/Group-IB &quot;Anunak&quot; report, &quot;&lt;a href=&quot;http://blog.malcovery.com/botnets-apts-and-malicious-emails&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;Botnets, APTS, and Malicious Emails&lt;/a&gt;&quot;)&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;table align=&quot;center&quot; cellpadding=&quot;0&quot; cellspacing=&quot;0&quot; class=&quot;tr-caption-container&quot; style=&quot;margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;tbody&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-I3CjWtkA39o/VqVKV76dUhI/AAAAAAAABAw/VeBpXU2L-H4/s1600/Zeus.Logs.For.Sale.jpg&quot; imageanchor=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;&quot;&gt;&lt;img border=&quot;0&quot; height=&quot;127&quot; src=&quot;http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-I3CjWtkA39o/VqVKV76dUhI/AAAAAAAABAw/VeBpXU2L-H4/s320/Zeus.Logs.For.Sale.jpg&quot; width=&quot;320&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class=&quot;tr-caption&quot; style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;&gt;A &quot;Zeus Logs&quot; seller offers 240MB of logs for $300-$400 ... &lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/tbody&gt;&lt;/table&gt;&lt;br /&gt;A Criminal Complaint is only intended to show Probable Cause to open an investigation.&amp;nbsp; It does not require the same level of details as an Indictment, which charges the accused of committing specific criminal acts.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The Indictment came in April of 2014 ...&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-xneNLjqy1N0/VqVC0mQUNII/AAAAAAAABAM/U-zZJwWUSBI/s1600/Vovnenko.Indictment.jpg&quot; imageanchor=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;&quot;&gt;&lt;img border=&quot;0&quot; height=&quot;213&quot; src=&quot;http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-xneNLjqy1N0/VqVC0mQUNII/AAAAAAAABAM/U-zZJwWUSBI/s320/Vovnenko.Indictment.jpg&quot; width=&quot;320&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;The Indictment adds additional aliases (Tomas Rimkis, Darklife) and specific charges.&amp;nbsp; We&#39;ll focus on Charge One and Three, which are the ones he pleaded guilty to this week.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Count One:&amp;nbsp; Wire Fraud Conspiracy (18 u.s.c.Â§1349)&lt;br /&gt;From September 2010 to August 2012, VOVNENKO and his co-conspirators &quot;operated an international criminal organization that hacked into the computers of individual users and of companies in the United States and elsewhere, and used that access to steal data, including, among other things, user names and passwords for bank accounts and other online services, as well as debit and credit card nubmers and related personal identifying information.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; After stealing the Log-In Credentials and Payment Card Data, defendant VOVNENKO and his co-conspirators used that information to illegally access and withdraw money from bank accounts and to incur unauthorized charges using the payment card data.&quot;&amp;nbsp; They also sold the data using online forums to individuals and groups that in turn did other illegal things with the data.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The indictment states that VOVNENKO had a botnet of &quot;over 13,000 computers infected with malware&quot; and that several of the infected computers were in New Jersey.&amp;nbsp; At least part of the malware was the &quot;Zeus&quot; malware that specializes in stealing banking information and recording keystrokes of users.&amp;nbsp; At least one employee  (known as &quot;J. H.&quot; in the indictment) of the Victim 1 bank had his workstation infected and from that base, the botnet was able to contact and interact with computers located inside financial institutions.&amp;nbsp; Counts Three through Six of the indictment refer to the specific acts of logging in to J.H.&#39;s computer &quot;in related to felony violations  &lt;br /&gt;&lt;div data-canvas-width=&quot;90.24130898437502&quot; style=&quot;font-size: 18.5361px; left: 292.838px; top: 648.553px; transform: scaleX(0.963945);&quot;&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-family: inherit;&quot;&gt;18 U.S.C.Â§1349 and 18 U.S.C.Â§1030(a)(2)(C) and (c)(2)(B)(i) &lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-ffdCBdfp0jo/VqVFUydjg7I/AAAAAAAABAY/2UjllGUCNcc/s1600/Vovnenko.Plea.jpg&quot; imageanchor=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;&quot;&gt;&lt;img border=&quot;0&quot; height=&quot;250&quot; src=&quot;http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-ffdCBdfp0jo/VqVFUydjg7I/AAAAAAAABAY/2UjllGUCNcc/s320/Vovnenko.Plea.jpg&quot; width=&quot;320&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;By December of 2015, Vovnenko and his lawyers knew he was going to be found guilty on all charges, no ifs, ands, or buts.&amp;nbsp; They agreed to a plea agreement where Vovnenko took the rap for Count One and Count Three, agreeing that he could face a sentence of 20 years imprisonment and $250,000 fine.&amp;nbsp; Because he also faced the charge of Aggravated Identity Theft, there is an additional two year mandatory minimum sentence that cannot run concurrently with any other sentence.&amp;nbsp; Further, VOVNENKO understood that he may be required to pay restitution, and will likely be deported after his sentence is served.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Sentencing in this case is set to May 2, 2016.&amp;nbsp; At that time, a Money Judgement will also be made regarding the amount of Restitution that may be required.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Many more details about &quot;Flycracker&quot; (as he was known on Silk Road) or &quot;MUXACC1&quot; (as he was known on Twitter) are available from Brian Krebs&#39; story &lt;a href=&quot;http://krebsonsecurity.com/2015/10/hacker-who-sent-me-heroin-faces-charges-in-u-s/&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;&quot;Hacker Who Sent Me Heroin Faces Charges in U.S.&quot; &lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;</content><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml'
