&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div id=&quot;noticiaContenido&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; National Police agents have participated in a simultaneous operation  conducted in Spain, Italy, Belgium and Poland against a network of cyber  fraud.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; In this joint operation coordinated by Europol and Eurojust also they  participated British NCA agents and police in Italy and Belgium.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; There are 49 detainees -10 of them in Spain and there have been 28  homes in which 9,000 euros have been seized laptops, hard disks, phones,  tablets, credit cards and extensive documentation on the activities of  the network.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; Those arrested by intrusion techniques and social engineering, were  made to the control of corporate email accounts to interfere in  international financial transactions between different companies.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; Thus they managed to change the target bank accounts and thus appropriate the money illegally.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; The international coordination was established effectively through  Europol headquarters in The Hague and link to cybercrime agent of the  National Police.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; In this way it has enabled the operation has been developed jointly and  simultaneously in all countries where they lived active members of the  criminal structure dismantled.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; It also has received support personnel and Europol mobile office moved to places where it has intervened.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; &lt;b&gt;Modus operandi&lt;/b&gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; The cyber attack used by this criminal group is called  man-in-the-middle, which is to control email accounts, in the case of  medium and large European companies.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; The members of the network were reviewing the messages sent and  received from corporate accounts to detect requests for payment.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; Then modified the messages for payments were transferred to bank accounts controlled by the criminal group.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; These payments were charged by the criminal organization immediately through different means.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; The investigation, originating mainly from Nigeria, Cameroon and Spain,  then transferred the money out of the European Union through a  sophisticated network of money laundering transactions.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; The investigation culminated with the arrest of 49 people in Spain (10), Italy, Belgium and Poland.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; In addition there have been 28 homes, 8 in Spain, 2 in the UK and 18 in  Italy, where agents have seized 9,000 euros in cash (5000 in Italy and  4000 in Spain), laptops, hard drives, mobile tablets, credit cards and  extensive documentation on the activities of the network.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; The operation was carried out by officers of the Unit for Technological  Research and the Police Headquarters of Catalonia of the National  Police, the Italian Polizia di Stato, the Polish National Police and the  British National Crime Agency.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;h2&gt;UPDATE #3 -- The News From Poland&lt;/h2&gt;The Polish National Police have also issued a press release about the arrests made in Poland.&amp;nbsp; target=&quot;_blank&quot;&gt;MiÄdzynarodowa operacja Europolu i Eurojustu - w sumie zatrzymano 49 cyberprzestÄpcÃ³w&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;h2&gt;(International Operation of Europol and Eurojust - a Total of 49 Criminals Arrested)&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: normal;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt;Officers  Coordination Team Central Bureau of Investigation Police and Border  Guard as well as police officers Municipal Police Headquarters in Krakow  and the Department for Combating Cybercrime Regional Police  Headquarters in Krakow, acting under the supervision of Appellate  Prosecutor&#39;s Office in Krakow together with the police and law  enforcement authorities from Italy and Spain, with collaboration with  investigators from Belgium, Georgia and the UK and support of Europol  and Eurojust, figured out an international organized criminal group,  engaged in money laundering, originating, inter alia&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; from phishing attacks carried out against citizens of European countries.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; On the Polish territory had been detained this matter for a total of 18 people.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;i&gt;&lt;span style=&quot;font-weight: normal;&quot;&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/i&gt; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt;On June 9th and 10th,&amp;nbsp; Europol and Eurojust conducted an international action against cyber criminals.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; A total of 49 suspects have been detained.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; The activities were also conducted in Poland.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; Yesterday, in the province of Malopolska police activity was carried  out in this case, one of the most important leading to the  arrest of five people, including the man who organized criminal dealings on  Polish territory.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; The Central Investigation Bureau Police seized more than 160 thousand from phishing.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; In total, the Polish were detained in that case 18 people.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; According to estimates investigators, members of criminal group could  &quot;launder&quot; a total of over 7.7 million (this amount coming only from the  crimes committed in our country).&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; Detained charges of fraud, money laundering and participation in an organized criminal group.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; On account of the suspect threatened penalties and fines secured property value of 1.8 million.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; Results of &quot;Operation Triangle&quot; are the result of large-scale  investigations carried out in Italy, Spain and Poland (Central Bureau of  Investigation Police Department with the participation of cybercrime  Police Headquarters in Krakow under the supervision of Appellate  Prosecutor&#39;s Office in Krakow).&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; The aim was to break organized crime groups engaged in phishing on the Internet.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; These types of crimes are carried out by specialized criminals who use the Internet to commit fraud.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; In addition criminals from exploiting cyberspace to &quot;laundering&quot; of money, proceeds of crime.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; In this way, embezzlement made substantial amounts of money from victims throughout Europe.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; In parallel, the investigation showed the existence of international fraud on a massive scale, extortion million in short time.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; The suspects, mainly from Nigeria and Cameroon, upload illegal profits  outside the European Union through a complex network of transactions  related to money laundering.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; In preparation for the run yesterday and today operations, Eurojust  coordinated the gathering of information from various law enforcement  agencies, as well as organized several coordination meetings with  representatives of national authorities from Italy, Spain, Polish,  Belgium and Great Britain.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; With all these joint efforts, coordination center was established who  carried out the operation with the support Team. Analysis Affairs  Eurojust, the European Centre for the fight against Cybercrime Europol  (EC3) and the Joint Task d.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; Cybercrime (JCAT) - a new European institution created to assist investigations to combat cybercrime.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; Joint action brought excellent results, while she realized that joining  forces selected EU agencies and national authorities can successfully  contribute to the fight against one of the most difficult to detect  forms of contemporary crime.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; Teresa-Angela Camelio, National Assistant Representative of Italy to  Eurojust, commented: &quot;Eurojust played a key role in promoting the  agendas of EU efforts in combating this type of crime, which requires  knowledge, cooperation and coordination between all involved national  and international actors.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; The results of the two-day operation are a clear signal to criminals that they will be prosecuted in every jurisdiction. &quot;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; Phishing on the Internet: This type of cybercrime, carried out by  organized criminal groups, depends on gaining access to passwords and  names (nicknames) of users for illegal activities.&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; Criminals replace respective owners information through &quot;phishing&quot;  their data and thereby gain access to their accounts, which means access  to the money the victims and their customers.&lt;/span&gt; Credentials&lt;span class=&quot;notranslate&quot;&gt; obtained in this way by organized criminal groups hurts many  Internet clients, while generating billions of euros of profits for  organized crime &quot;pop-ups&quot; </title><content type='html'>There is a new trap on the Internet that seems to be growing in popularity in the form of a Tech Support pop-up Window.&amp;nbsp; The first of these I saw was last Tuesday, March 24, 2015.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;h2&gt;Norton Scam&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;br /&gt;While reviewing some pharmaceutical spam web pages, we were suddenly forwarded to the page:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;alert.norton.com.pctechhelpforyou.com/index-15mac.html&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-SY1mZQbxVJM/VRlC0ftW-2I/AAAAAAAAA3I/-p5Y4lpmsJ8/s1600/pctechhelpforyou.com.jpg&quot; imageanchor=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;&quot;&gt;&lt;img border=&quot;0&quot; src=&quot;http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-SY1mZQbxVJM/VRlC0ftW-2I/AAAAAAAAA3I/-p5Y4lpmsJ8/s1600/pctechhelpforyou.com.jpg&quot; height=&quot;214&quot; width=&quot;320&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;Immediately after this page rendering, a pop-up window is repeatedly displayed insisting that we need to call the telephone number 1-888-884-7058, ringing a bell each time the window is displayed.&amp;nbsp; The pop-up is so insistent that it is very difficult to get past the pop-up to close the browser.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-ueJCLeYWN6c/VRlGb45zY-I/AAAAAAAAA3U/L7mvQb-cS0I/s1600/pctechhelpforyou.888.884.7058.jpg&quot; imageanchor=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;&quot;&gt;&lt;img border=&quot;0&quot; src=&quot;http://1.bp.blogspot.com/-ueJCLeYWN6c/VRlGb45zY-I/AAAAAAAAA3U/L7mvQb-cS0I/s1600/pctechhelpforyou.888.884.7058.jpg&quot; height=&quot;400&quot; width=&quot;307&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;Despite the fact that this pop-up is warning me about my APPLE COMPUTER, the original trigger that we encountered was in a Windows 7 Virtual Machine.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Looking at the source code for the page we see that we are dealing with JavaScript that has several tricks, including &quot;right-click disable&quot; and an annoying command &quot;window.onbeforeunload = PopIt&quot;.&amp;nbsp; Actions such as &quot;document.onmouseup&quot; and &quot;document.captureEvents(event.MOUSEDOWN)&quot; help to keep control of the window, making it nearly impossible to close the browser, which also sets itself to appear in the Center of the screen, obscuring other opportunities to deal with the warning.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;h2&gt;iPad / Mac Pop-ups&lt;/h2&gt;&lt;br /&gt;This weekend, I found myself looking at a very similar variant, this time on an iPad, where it was even more difficult to get rid of the pop-up!&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://3.bp.blogspot.com/-0JQqS1YyLUU/VRlJBtx4lpI/AAAAAAAAA3g/T9yW_NMvAio/s1600/safarisecurityissue.com.jpg&quot; imageanchor=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;margin-left: 1em; margin-right: width=&quot;320&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;Because of the lack of mouse or keyboard on the iPad, this version of the browser pop-up was especially hard to deal with.&amp;nbsp; The pop-up prevented me from being able to exit Safari!&amp;nbsp; In the end, it was necessary to power off the iPad, power back on, and then use the &quot;Settings&quot; tab to clear my history and settings.&amp;nbsp; By default an iPad Safari browser returns you to the most recently visited page, which unfortunately was this pop-up!&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;As I explored this version, I found that the current domain was hosted on the IP address 198.143.166.36.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; This same IP address was also hosting a great number of other suspicious domain names,which began to show up on last several of the links on that page appear to belong to a company that does support for Intuit Quickbooks, however &quot;JoinRemote.me&quot; is a remote control tool.&amp;nbsp; When the telephone number is called, the tech support person walks the customer through entering a tech support code by visiting &quot;JoinRemote.me&quot;:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://4.bp.blogspot.com/-y38W-bWRpgY/VRlqpVRJzVI/AAAAAAAAA4c/z7psQwe6DBw/s1600/joinme.jpg&quot; imageanchor=&quot;1&quot; height=&quot;172&quot; width=&quot;320&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;When that is done, the customer service technician is provided remote control access to the computer to &quot;clean it up.&quot;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;A friend from MalwareBytes has documented similar scammy behavior where a tax-season Intuit helper website ends up charging for a malware removal.&amp;nbsp; See Jerome&#39;s blog here:&amp;nbsp; &lt;a href=&quot;https://blog.malwarebytes.org/fraud-scam/2014/03/the-tax-season-tech-support-scam/&quot;&gt;https://blog.malwarebytes.org/fraud-scam/2014/03/the-tax-season-tech-support-scam/&lt;/a&gt;.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;By reviewing the Apple Discussion boards, we also saw evidence that several other people were struggling with these pop-up messages:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;div /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;a both; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: left;&quot;&gt;&amp;nbsp;Continuing to explore through the Apple discussion forums, we found evidence that this was also discussed back on September 2, 2014 in this post by Carlton Chin:&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-mmwiCvqv9uk/VRlLwrFqR5I/AAAAAAAAA4A/lxTzfhDfesg/s1600/apple.discussion.6516975.jpg&quot; imageanchor=&quot;1&quot; both; text-align: left;&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: left;&quot;&gt;The September file had a different domain name, and a different telephone number, but could it be shown to be the same scammers?&amp;nbsp; Was applesecurityalert.com on 1-866-782-9808 related to safarisystemissue.com on 1-800-632-9078?&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: left;&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: left;&quot;&gt;Back to Passive DNS to try to find out.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: left;&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: left;&quot;&gt;According to the Internet Identity Passive DNS system, AppleSecurityAlert.com was hosted on the IP address 50.87.153.101 beginning on August 8, 2014.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: left;&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: left;&quot;&gt;That IP address ALSO hosted i-xperts.us, ixperts.net, joinremote.me, and quickbo0ks.com, all of which were also found on both the August/September IP (50.87.153.101) and the March 2015 IP (198.143.166.36).&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: left;&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;Several of the attack sites that share these IP addresses are Microsoft imitators rather than Apple.&amp;nbsp; One example is &quot;online-window-security.com&quot; pictured below:&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://3.bp.blogspot.com/--79R9tctIek/VRlokD_FmqI/AAAAAAAAA4Q/shLBBwJOat8/s1600/online-window.jpg&quot; imageanchor=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;margin-left: 1em; margin-right: 1em;&quot;&gt;&lt;img border=&quot;0&quot; src=&quot;http://3.bp.blogspot.com/--79R9tctIek/VRlokD_FmqI/AAAAAAAAA4Q/shLBBwJOat8/s1600/online-window.jpg&quot; height=&quot;363&quot; width=&quot;400&quot; /&gt;&amp;nbsp;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;Imitating Microsoft Security Essentials&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: left;&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: left;&quot;&gt;Bottom line - anyone seeing one of these pop-ups suggesting that a telephone number be called for support is DEFINITELY dealing with a scammer and should terminate the session immediately. &lt;/div&gt;&lt;div class=&quot;separator&quot; style=&quot;clear: both; text-align: left;&quot;&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br scheme="http://www.blogger.com/atom/ns#" term="Peggy Smedley"/><title type='text'>Connected World Conference 2015 </title><content type='html'>This week I&#39;ve been attending the Connected World Conference 2015, hosted here in Birmingham,&amp;nbsp; Alabama.&amp;nbsp; Connected World&#39;s editor-in-chief, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.peggysmedleyshow.com/&quot;&gt;Peggy Smedley, hosts a weekly radio program &lt;/a&gt;that focuses on the Internet of Things (IoT) which their industry has called M2M for many years before the IoT tag came along.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; Peggy&#39;s website has a great tutorial on the &lt;a href=&quot;http://connectedworld.com/m2m-premier/&quot;&gt;Machine To Machine&lt;/a&gt; networking technologies and the many ways in which they communicate, but I think nothing really brought the point home to me until I attended the Connected World Awards dinner last night.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;If you are thinking about Cyber Security and the Internet of Things, here are quite a few interesting applications I learned about in the dinner last night.&amp;nbsp; The full range of &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.prweb.com/releases/2015/02/prweb12540329.htm&quot;&gt;Connected World Award winners are listed here&lt;/a&gt;, but these were a few that really caught my attention.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.att.com/edo/chooseATT/chooseATT.jsp?primary=010000&amp;amp;pageTitle=Our%20Resources#/OurResources&quot;&gt;AT&amp;amp;T Drive Studio&lt;/a&gt; - The AT&amp;amp;T Drive Studio in Atlanta, Georgia - The AT&amp;amp;T Drive Studioâ¢ is the first connected car innovation center  in the U.S. to be opened by a wireless carrier. And AT&amp;amp;T is inviting  the world&#39;s most innovative companies and developers to come create the  future of connected cars.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://apartmentguardian.com/&quot;&gt;ApartmentGuardian&lt;/a&gt;, powered by RacoWireless, won the Gold award in the PERS category.&amp;nbsp; Property managers can use the technology in many ways, from protecting their Lone Workers with a personal safety button (reminiscent of the &quot;I&#39;ve Fallen and I Can&#39;t Get Up!&quot; button that you might buy for your grandmother) to a system for identifying guests to the property in a combined ID card and biometrics solution for visitors to the property, and innovative Security Panels.&amp;nbsp; The use of low-power radio technology as a backup to &quot;wall power&quot; for keeping your building security and alarm systems online and active during power failures.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Two companies won awards in the Lighting/Manufacturing category.&amp;nbsp; In both situations the recipients, Atlantic States and Clow Water Systems, were able to achieve amazing savings in both energy and true financial savings by putting in intelligent lighting systems.&amp;nbsp; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.synapse-wireless.com/wireless-lighting-control/sensors/daylight-harvesting-occupancy-sensor-lightsense&quot;&gt;Synapse Wireless&lt;/a&gt; allows the light fixtures in both organizations to be controlled remotely and through connecting all of the lights in a &quot;Mesh&quot; system - a cloud of lighting services that are in constant communications with one another.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;table align=&quot;center&quot; cellpadding=&quot;0&quot; cellspacing=&quot;0&quot; class=&quot;tr-caption-container&quot; style=&quot;margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto; text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;tbody&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.synapse-wireless.com/images/images/products/Synapse-SNAP-LightSense-diagram.jpg&quot; imageanchor=&quot;1&quot; style=&quot;margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;&quot;&gt;&lt;img border=&quot;0&quot; src=&quot;http://www.synapse-wireless.com/images/images/products/Synapse-SNAP-LightSense-diagram.jpg&quot; height=&quot;114&quot; width=&quot;320&quot; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;tr&gt;&lt;td class=&quot;tr-caption&quot; style=&quot;text-align: center;&quot;&gt;SNAP LightSense from Synapse Wireless&lt;/td&gt;&lt;/tr&gt;&lt;/tbody&gt;&lt;/table&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.mesh-systems.com/company/events&quot;&gt;Mesh Systems&lt;/a&gt; was the IoT-enabler for BUNN who received an award in the Remote Equipment Management category.&amp;nbsp;&amp;nbsp; You have heard of the IoT refrigerator, but BUNN has created the IoT Coffee pot!&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;One of the most interesting M2M applications was &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.gemalto.com/press/Pages/Gemalto-M2M-connectivity-solution-helps-deliver-green-energy-to-remote-communities-without-electricity.aspx&quot;&gt;SOLARKIOSK&lt;/a&gt;, which is using Gemalto&#39;s Cinterion modules to deliver remote connectivity and a web-interface for monitoring power production to a mobile unit about the size of a food truck that can be deployed in remote areas, including extremely rural Africa, to provide power and cellular connectivity to areas that lack reliable power.&amp;nbsp; The first such unit was featured in this story &quot;&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.gizmag.com/worlds-first-solarkiosk-ethiopia/23382/&quot;&gt;First SolarKiosk opened in Ethiopia&lt;/a&gt;.&quot;&amp;nbsp; The creator, Lars KrÃ¼ckeberg, was featured in a TED talk about the technology as well.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The IoT enables some interesting Fleet Management capabilities as well.&amp;nbsp; &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.calamp.com/system/files/resources/case-studies/cityofdayton.pdf&quot;&gt;CalAmp and the City of Dayton&lt;/a&gt; received an award for their system for monitoring and protecting their fleet of 210 snow removal vehicles.&amp;nbsp; The system, called GovOutlook, turns itself on when a key is inserted into a vehicle, and requires a City of Dayton employee id badge to be scanned to prevent lockdown and alarming.&amp;nbsp; The system also provides safety for the drivers, who are out on the roads, often in the middle of the night, plowing the 1800 lane miles of snow-covered roads in the city of Dayton.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;The focus of our &lt;a href=&quot;http://connectedworld.com/conference/agenda/&quot;&gt;Connected World Conference&lt;/a&gt; this year has been on Cyber Security ... speakers including myself and John Grimes from UAB, JD Sherry from Trend Micro, Seth Danberry from Grid32, Jonathan Ratner from Sixgill, Brian Zaugg from Authentic8 and others joined to share our thoughts on Cyber Security to those who have come from the Internet of Things / Machine 2 Machine world.&amp;nbsp; I was glad I participated and learned much more about the IoT world!&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Thanks, Peggy!&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;To learn more about the IoT, please do check out &lt;a href=&quot;http://connectedworld.com/magazine/&quot;&gt;Connected World Magazine&lt;/a&gt; and check in with the &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.peggysmedleyshow.com/&quot;&gt;Peggy Smedley Radio&lt;/a&gt; show.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;</content><link rel='replies' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://garwarner.blogspot.com/feeds/8487392714652876485/comments/default' title='Post Comments'/><link rel='replies' type='text/html' href='http://garwarner.blogspot.com/2015/02/connected-world-conference-2015.html#comment-form' title='0 Comments'/><link rel='edit' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/35783026/posts/default/8487392714652876485'/><link rel='self' type='application/atom+xml' href='http://www.blogger.com/feeds/35783026/posts/default/8487392714652876485'/><link rel='alternate' type='text/html' href='http://garwarner.blogspot.com/2015/02/connected-world-conference-2015.html' title='Connected World Conference 2015 '/><author><name>Gary Warner, UAB / PhishMe</name><uri>http://www.blogger.com/profile/10822366940133384061</uri><email>noreply@blogger.com</email><gd:image rel='http://schemas.google.com/g/2005#thumbnail' width='32' height='32' src='//3.bp.blogspot.com/-css1_Txun8Q/VyeaNCPlI_I/AAAAAAAABEY/suKqHx3YvqAccGORXzJeg6Ie7zJ_LcjTgCK4B/s220/20792047913_7f098b2b60_o%2B%2528638x640%2529.jpg'/></author><thr:total>0</thr:total></entry></feed>
